A few days before the election, he met with journalist Euronews.
Euronews: Mr. Meimarakis, welcome to Euronews!
Vangelis Meimaracis: Thank you for the invitation.
Euronews: Nine months ago, your party suffered a crushing defeat, losing to the Syriza coalition, but now, judging by the polls, the New Democracy has equaled it in popularity.
What has changed during this time?
Vangelis Meimarakis: Greece has changed, and so did we.
Mr. Tsipras lied a lot in January last year.
Nine months ago, Greece had a budget surplus and prospects for economic growth.
Now the country has a budget deficit and a high unemployment rate.
Investors left because Mr. Tsipras chased them away.
Over the past nine months, the Greeks have had the opportunity to assess the situation in which the country was in January, and the false promises of Mr. Tsipras.
And now they can easily compare what has been promised with what really happened.
Everyday life became noticeably worse compared to January, when the situation improved, and this applied to the majority of Greek citizens.
Euronews: But you say that if you win the election, you will seek alliances with other parties, including SYRIZA.
Vangelis Meimarakis: The point is that, as we have understood in recent years, Greece cannot move forward without understanding and cooperation.
And it is no coincidence that in all other countries where salvation programs have operated or are still operating, political forces and all the ruling parties have come together to implement the program by which they reached agreement without renouncing their political or ideological autonomy.
That is why I firmly believe that at the current stage only the cooperation of political forces and institutions will allow the country to move forward.
Euronews: Your party voted in support of the agreement between Mr. Tsipras and the country’s creditors.
If you become the new prime minister on Monday, will you follow this agreement, or will you try to change it at least in part?
Vangelis Meimarakis: In fact, we voted for the movement of Greece on the European path, because it is well represented to what the disastrous consequences would lead the country’s withdrawal from the EU.
Now Europe is helping us by providing subsidies to our farmers for their products, we have solidarity funds, the Juncker package and assistance in the banking sector.
All this would have been lost if there had been no treaty with Europe.
But the current austerity measures were the result of Mr. Tsipras negotiated.
I know that Europe does not want to destroy us.
Europe wants to help us.
Thus, if Europe sees that the new Greek government during the first year in power wants to restore order, acts rationally and makes it clear that the country has a strong political will to implement the rescue program, then, I am sure, all the commitments made that cannot be fulfilled because of the fact that lead to a recession can again become the subject of negotiations, but only after a certain time.
It would be a mistake to believe that in the first year of the new agreement we will be able to return to negotiations with our creditors, as they expect the full implementation of the agreement.
If we want to regain their credibility, we must continue to privatize, reforms and structural changes that have been agreed to continue to enjoy the benefits of EU funding and the great investment opportunities that we must open up for a better understanding and cooperation with Europe.
Unfortunately, during the talks, the Tsipras government did not provide any serious arguments on many key political issues, which we found out when discussing these issues with our European counterparts.
I can give you an example related to the income of farmers.
We explained to our European partners that we are not talking about a fixed monthly income, and therefore it cannot be fully taxed in advance.
We were told that Tsipras' ministers never talked about it.
That is, the Greek ministers were not prepared and ill-informed, and therefore unsuccessfully negotiated and concluded an unsuccessful agreement.
Euronews: If you win the election, you will soon be at the same table with Mr. Juncker, Hollande, Mrs. Merkel and other European leaders.
Will what you tell them what your predecessor Antonis Samaras has told them?
Vangelis Meymarakis: First of all, I will explain to them that by the end of 2014 we tried to best implement the 2012 agreement, bypassing the sharp corners in it.
We have been promoting reforms forward.
Of course, we lacked the necessary determination and speed, but we acted in extraordinary circumstances.
The market fell, and there were no potential buyers willing to pay the price that suited the Greek government.
I was the speaker of parliament at the time, I managed to agree on the views of the three parliamentary groups that then constituted a government majority.
And despite their serious ideological differences on key bills, we had a working parliament, and this is in the presence of populists and extremists, as well as mass demonstrations that took place outside.
And we were able to bring the country to a normal situation that would continue to improve if the process had not been interrupted by early general elections that were the result of the December presidential election.
Euronews: In recent weeks, a massive flow of refugees has been moving through Greece.
What do you think about this situation, and about the reaction of the European countries in which these people aspire?
Vangelis Meymarakis: The refugee crisis is a time bomb that we have to deal with after winning the election.
