"Sonogenetics" allows you to control brain cells with sound waves
The video shows the nematodes changing the direction of movement at the moment when they are exposed to sound pulses.
Scientists have bred worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can be controlled using slips of sound waves.
Tiny nematodes change the direction of movement at the moment when they are exposed to sound pulses, too high, so that the human ear can hear them.
Impulses have an effect by activating neurons genetically modified to use membrane channels that respond to ultrasound waves.
Researchers manage brain activity with light
Scientists said that the worms demonstrate the capabilities of a new technique called “sonogenetics”, the essence of which is to use ultrasound to excite certain cells of the brain, heart and muscles, while the source of ultrasound is located outside the body.
Srikant Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute, La Hoya, California, told the Guardian that this technique could one day replace deep brain stimulation - an invasive procedure in which electrical impulses are sent to the human brain and which is used in the treatment of Parkinson's disease.
Nematodes worms usually do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they began to react when they were placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found that the bubbles amplify ultrasonic waves, which then penetrate into the body of the worms.
Enhanced ultrasonic waves affect structures called “TRP-4 ion channels” found in the membranes of some worm cells.
Ultrasonic waves cause these ion channels to open and excite the cells that are associated with them, according to a report in Nature Communications.
To create nematodes that can be controlled by ultrasound, Chalasani made genetic modifications of the worms, so that their motor neurons used TRP-4 ion channels.
During the use of ultrasound to influence modified organisms, sound waves were amplified with microscopic bubbles and injected into the bodies of worms, activating modified motor neurons.
This technique is similar to the one that is used in "ophotogenetics" - a new direction that allows scientists to turn on and off neurons using light pulses.
Chalasani argues that compared to this technique, sonetical may have some benefits.
Unlike light, which is delivered to the desired area of the brain on fiber, low-frequency ultrasound waves pass freely through the tissues of the body, so for their delivery you do not need to go inside the skull.
“We believe that in order to treat some neurological diseases in a clinical setting, the use of gene therapy and therapeutic viruses will be able to temporarily make human neurons sensitive to the ultrasound signal,” Chalasani said.
He added that, in addition, the technique can be applied to muscle and insulin-producing cells.
