Imported yachts will be exempt from customs duties.
The Ministry of Economic Development intends to temporarily exempt imported yachts and other floating funds for recreation and sports from customs duties and taxes.
Corresponding changes to the list of preferential goods for temporary duty-free import were prepared by the Ministry on behalf of the government of the Russian Federation.
This was reported to Izvestia by the assistant Minister of economic development Elena Lashkina.
In June 2015, the Prime Minister of the Russian Federation Dmitry Medvedev, following the results of a trip to the Crimea, instructed a number of departments - the Ministry of Economic Development, the Ministry of Transport of the Russian Federation, the Ministry of Culture, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the Ministry of Emergency Situations, the FSB, the FCS, Rosturizm - to prepare proposals for creating favorable conditions for yachting in the coastal zones of the country.
In turn, experts note that the main problem is the complete lack of infrastructure for storing, maintenance and maintenance of yachts.
Owners prefer to keep their ships abroad - about € 200 million annually go to the treasury of European countries for the maintenance, repair and maintenance of yachts.
The Ministry of Economic Development of Russia has prepared a draft decision of the Council of the Eurasian Economic Commission “On Amendments to the List of Goods Temporarily Imported with a Full Conditional Exemption from Payment of Customs Duties”, which provides for the provision of a full conditional exemption from customs duties, taxes in respect of imported yachts and other floating funds for recreation and sports.
According to the ministry, this, of course, will contribute to the creation of favorable conditions for the development of yachting in the coastal zones of the country, ”said Lashkina.
This issue was submitted to the subcommission on customs-tariff, non-tariff regulation, protective measures in foreign trade of the Government Commission for Economic Development and Integration, the meeting of which took place in September, and following the discussion was also approved by the departments.
As noted by the representative of the Ministry of economic development, the proposed measure for full conditional release during importation is essentially a benefit.
Therefore, after the approval of the minutes of the meeting of the subcommittee in the government of the Russian Federation, the Ministry of Economic Development will submit a proposal to the Eurasian Economic Commission for discussion with the EAEU member states, Lashkina explained.
The list of imported goods, which are completely exempt from customs duties, taxes, includes goods necessary to assist foreign economic activity and international cooperation, for use in the field of science, culture, cinematography, sports and tourism, for the provision of international assistance, etc. Among them are service equipment (personal computers, typewriters), instrumentation and measuring equipment, drilling equipment, stage costumes and scenery, mobile laboratories and workshops, water skis, racing cars, motorcycles, sports aircraft, books, newspapers, magazines, musical instruments and objects for religious rites.
The press service of the Ministry of Transport of the Russian Federation told Izvestia that they prepared mandatory resolutions on the seaports of Kerch, Sevastopol, Yalta, Feodosia and Evpatoria, which provide for a simplified procedure for the registration of the call and exit of small-dimensional, sports sailing and pleasure vessels to the seaport.
The Ministry of Transport instructed the captains of the sea ports of Crimea to ensure the application of a simplified procedure for the entry of small, sports sailing and pleasure craftsmen into the seaport and the exit of listed ships from the seaport.
Also, the Ministry of Transport has prepared draft orders of the government of the Russian Federation on the approval of the borders of the seaports of Crimea.
In relation to Yalta and Feodosia, orders have already been adopted, the rest are in the process of coordination, the press service of the department noted.
According to the Ministry of Transport, state supervision, classification and examination, state registration in respect of small vessels used for non-commercial purposes should be carried out by the Republic of Crimea and Sevastopol.
The problem is that in Russia it is extremely difficult with yachting precisely because of the poorly developed infrastructure.
If you look at the south of Italy and France, then there it is a whole constantly developing industry, in which a large number of people are involved.
In Russia, virtually everything stands still.
Our coast is uninteresting, the only piece where you can operate yachts all year round is the Black Sea in the Sochi, Gelendzhik, Novorossiysk, Anapa.
But the great difficulty is that in this area there are very strict rules of the border service: in order to go for a walk on a yacht, you need to issue a lot of permissions.
In addition, inside Russia, the yacht has nowhere to refuel.
For two days it can go with its fuel, and then there is a problem where to take it, - says the sales director of the company Nordmarine Denis Novikov.
As for the storage of yachts, in Moscow and St. Petersburg now there are special hangars for yachts up to 30 m. Also, the yachts are sent for storage to Turkey, Finland, Sweden and Germany.
Novikov noted that yacht buyers are rich people, but with the onset of the crisis, the demand for yachts has decreased.
