Kiev broke the nuclear union.
Kiev officially issued the refusal of Ukraine to cooperate with Russia on the completion of the Khmelnytsky nuclear power plant.
The Verkhovna Rada on Wednesday on the second attempt still voted for the termination of the agreement with Moscow.
Agreements for the completion of the third and fourth blocks were signed in 2010-2012, but it was not possible to start implementing the project.
On Wednesday, the Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine adopted a law that terminates the agreement concluded in 2010-2012 with the Russian Federation on the construction of the third and fourth unit at the Khmelnytskyi nuclear power plant.
The bill submitted by the government of the country was carried out only from the second vote, for the first time it was supported by 210 deputies with the necessary minimum of 226, but then 234 members of parliament voted for the project.
The Khmelnytsky NPP laid under the USSR under the original project was supposed to have four power units of 1 GW with VVER reactors, but only two managed to build.
Negotiations with Moscow on the completion led to the conclusion of an intergovernmental agreement by 2010, in 2011-2012 the Verkhovna Rada adopted relevant laws.
Since there were no funds in the budget of Ukraine, it was assumed that it would be necessary to build blocks on the loan of the Russian side, but the funds were not allocated.
After the coup in Kiev in February 2014 and the subsequent cooling in relations between the two countries, Kiev began to curtail relations with Moscow in the nuclear industry, announcing the refusal to cooperate on the Khmelnytsky nuclear power plant and on the project for the construction of a nuclear fuel plant in Ukraine.
The only area where relations have remained, there was still the purchase of fuel in the Russian Federation for existing Ukrainian nuclear power plants (provided about half of the generation of electricity in the country), since while the Ukrainian NNEGC "Energoatom" has nothing to replace Russian supplies.
From the plans to complete the Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant with another contractor in Ukraine have not yet finally refused: back in 2014, Kiev announced negotiations with the Czech Skoda JS.
