FedEx revenue is mixed, a decline in forecasts for 2016.
FedEx reported on the disappointing results of the last quarter, and the shipping service giant reduced the forecast for annual profits due to falling demand for freight services and rising costs in its division of land transportation.
The company also said that it plans to hire about 55 000 seasonal workers for the holidays.
At the same time, FedEx announced last year that it would hire 50 000 temporary workers for the holidays.
Its shares fell by about 2.5 percent in preliminary auction 45 minutes before the opening of the exchange on Wednesday.
FedEx Corp. Said he plans to earn $10.40 to $10.90 in the fiscal year, which ends next May, which is 20 cents less than in the previous forecast.
Analysts assumed $10.84 according to the FactSet review.
The decline in the forecast is observed despite the increase in rates by an average of 4.9 percent, which will enter into force on January 4, and an increase in fees for ground transportation of heavy or overall cargo, which begins in November.
The company said it still plans revenue growth from last year by cutting costs, rising gross revenue and rising online trading.
Chairman and CEO Fred Smith said the company "worked stably taking into account weak, compared to the forecast, economic conditions, especially in production and world trade."
Plans to hire labor during the holidays were announced the day after the competitor’s statement, UPS, that they plan to hire an additional 95 000 employees, about the same as they hired last year.
For the quarter that ended on August 31, FedEx earned $692 million, 6 percent more than a year earlier.
Revenue per share was $ 2.42, close to the forecast of an average of 2.44 dollars per share conducted by Zacks Investment Research by a survey of 12 analysts.
Income increased by 5%, to 12.3 billion. dollars.
Six analysts surveyed by Zacks expected 12.23 billion. dollars.
FedEx has suffered a decline in the international transport sector in recent years, leading to a lack of growth in its express transportation division.
However, the boom in online purchases dramatically improved the results in FedEx Ground.
In the last quarter, revenue from land transport increased by 29%, but operating income remained largely unchanged due to increased costs for large shipments and self-insurance.
The express transportation unit has received higher returns due to higher base rates, while in the freight sector the income fell due to higher labor costs.
At preliminary auctions, about an hour before the opening of the exchange, FedEx shares fell by $3.85 or 2.5 percent to $150.15.
They closed Tuesday, falling 11 percent over the year and 17 percent below the June 11 record.
At the most anticipated meeting in a few years, the leaders of the Federal Reserve will spend two days this week at a 27-foot table of Honduran mahogany wood, deciding whether it is not time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in almost ten years.
At one end, a richly decorated meeting room with a height of two floors above them will hang a wall image of the United States.
This map is a reminder that the chairman of the Federal Reserve, Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the country’s economic interests above all others.
The central bank received a double order from Congress: to maximize employment in the United States and keep stable prices here.
But since the Great Recession, the leaders of the Federal System have recognized that there is a third, unwritten instruction: financial stability.
And that third order could prove to be an unknown factor in an almost forecasted decision on Thursday, whether the U.S. economy is ready to break away from the unpriencious stimulus provided by the nearly zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
Even though most of the data show a steady growth in the economy, recent upheavals in global financial markets can keep already cautious executives of the Federal system from adding volatility by raising the base rate on federal funds – even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and most important subject to consideration,” Lindsey told M. Piegza, Chief Economist at the Brokerage Company Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“However, I think if they were looking for a reason not to raise rates, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough to give them an excuse to wait further,” she said.
There is no consensus on what will be done in the Federal Reserve, which in itself provokes fluctuations in the financial market.
Approximately half of economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg predicted an increase in interest rates this week.
Financial markets, however, expect the Federal system to refrain from this, while the key indicator shows only about a 30 percent chance of a rapid rise.
This could lead to a fall in the stock market if the Federal system raises the rate, provided that those who make decisions do not soften the blow by the promise that the next increase will not soon be.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones index rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16 599.85.
The take-off was triggered by expectations that the Federal System’s strategy would reliance this week,” said John Lonsky, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research.
“There will be a surprise if the Federal system raises rates at this point in time,” he said.
If the Federal Reserve’s management does, “they will have to go far in approving their strategy to keep financial markets in their hands so they don’t panic.”
Other experts objected that the rate hike could reassure financial markets as it would remove uncertainty about how the Federal system would operate.
Just a month ago, the Federal system seemed to be leaning to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, taking the first small step in a slow tightening of financial conditions, which could confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expects a rate hike this year, despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although the emergence of new jobs slowed in August, the growth of the labor market was stable this year.
Unemployment declined to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years, and at almost the level that the Federal System considers full employment.
Wage growth shows signs of acceleration.
And, while inflation continues to be below the central bank’s annual target of 2%, the Federal system management said the key was the temporary effect of a sharp drop in oil prices.
The economy “can cope with higher rates, and needs them, given the reduction in the labor market,” said Ian Sheferdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world began to shake at the end of last month, after China devalued its currency.
The average Dow Jones stock index for industrial stocks fell by as much as 16% relative to a record high in May, as investors feared that a slowdown in the Chinese economy could slow down global growth.
The market has partially regained its position this month, and the Dow Jones index is now about 10% below the high May value.
For the management of the Federal Reserve System, market indignation further complicates the difficult calculations of the period of interest rate increase.
“In the absence of information about what happened in the financial markets and news about the weakness of the Chinese economy in the past few weeks, they would have been twisting the screws at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oiner, senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former employee of the Federal Reserve System.
Now, according to his forecasts, they will wait at least a month to gain more control over the consequences.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the consequences for the American economy can be, and they have almost no reliable data after the latest developments in China,” Oliner said.
The health of the world economy is not within the main concerns of the Federal system, and technically it should not be taken into account when making these decisions.
But essentially the Federal Reserve has become a global financial authority.
The influence of the Central Bank in recent years has been enormous.
