Four people, including a 4-year-old boy, were killed in southern Nepal as police began firing rubber bullets into a crowd protesting the country’s new constitution, a spokesman said on Wednesday.
The violence occurred on Tuesday evening in the district of Rupandai, about 175 miles west of Kathmandu, the capital of the country.
Bishnu Prasad Dakal, the head of the district police, reported that more than 1 000 protesters gathered at one of the police stations, some threw stones and incendiary bombs.
