Twenty police officers and five civilians were injured, he said.
It is not clear why rubber bullets, which are known to be killed, but they are traditionally used as a less lethal alternative have caused such a high mortality rate.
This clash was the last in a few weeks of violent protests in the southern, low-priced Nepal, where Mazei people claim that the new provinces formed under the new constitution will reduce their political influence.
The protests also took place in western Nepal, among Taru citizens who want to have their own state.
At least 40 people, including eleven police officers, have been killed in violent clashes since 10
August, when the four main political parties signed an agreement to divide the country into provinces, which was a decisive step towards a new constitution, but a very controversial issue in Nepal, which has been centrally managed for several centuries.
Work on the new constitution has been underway since 2008, but lawmakers have accelerated the process after a devastating earthquake that claimed the lives of thousands of people in April.
Lawmakers voted for the articles of the draft constitution in Kathmandu this week, and officials said that the new chapter will be signed by Sunday.
