Diabetics with minor obesity can help obesity surgery
A favorable effect after obesity surgery in people with minor obesity suffering from type 2 diabetes can last at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to say that diabetics with minor obesity live longer after obesity surgery than those who receive non-surgical treatment.
“The mortality statistics are not immediately manifested,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an obesity surgery expert who wrote about a new study in the JAMA Sundery editor’s column.
Obesity surgery, or bariatric surgery, uses a variety of methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the ability of organisms to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven to be effective for the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but the main studies have been conducted among people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a measure of weight relative to height, is considered normal at a value of 18.5 to 24.9.
A BMI 25 or higher suggests that a person is overweight, and people with a BMI above 30 are considered obese people.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1DzqDv.
For the new study, researchers from the Taiwanese Min-Shen General hospital used data collected since 2007, comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass surgery and sleeve gastrectomy, with a medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with minor obesity.
The average BMI value in those undergone surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of their involvement in the study.
At the same time, BMI in those who received non-surgical treatment for diabetes remains at about 29.
Among those who underwent surgery, 36% of diabetes were completely cured of diabetes, and partly - 28%.
In the group that received medical treatment, for comparison, a complete cure for diabetes was observed in only 1%, and partially - only about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “generally were better in the surgical group,” the authors say.
The researchers also monitored blood hemoglobin levels that reflected blood sugar levels in the dynamics.
Hemoglobin A1c is better to keep below 7%, the researchers write.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c level decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
In the therapeutic group, however, it remained stable, at about 8%.
But the best indicators of glycemic control, reflected by good hemoglobin levels A1c, did not reduce the mortality rate over the five years, according to the research chief Dr. Chi-Cheng-Soo and colleagues.
The research team also compared the two-type medical results.
In the fifth year, compared to the group that received the sleeve gastrectomy, the bypass group lost more weight (18.7 kg vs. 14.2 kg), achieved a greater decrease in BMI (by 7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1%), and was also closer to full remission of diabetes (46.9% vs. 16.7%).
Although the new study does not show the benefits of the surgical method in terms of life expectancy after five years, there are evidences from the study of people who are overweight in Sweden that surgical treatment does lead to an increase in life expectancy, according to Blackstone from the College of Medicine in g. Phoenix, University of Arizona.
According to a Swedish study for obese people who have chosen bariatric intervention, the probability of dying for 15 years was about 29% lower compared to a group that used more traditional methods.
Although the new study has not shown an increase in life expectancy, Blackstone noted that it encourages people with an IMT below 35 interested in such a procedure.
“The report here is very important because it claims that such surgery is safe in a low-Bam group where there is no increased risk of mortality or kidney disease,” she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors should begin to take weight seriously once the patient’s BMI gets into the range between 27 and 30.
“I think we’ve been waiting too long to get people to take it seriously,” she said.
It seems to me that as soon as they accumulate genetic changes that cause obesity and diabetes in their bodies, it is very difficult to reverse it.
