Hewlett-Packard will cut to 30 000 jobs
Hewlett-Packard aims to cut from 25 000 to 30 000 jobs as part of its restructuring and reduction of service costs.
In the same year, Hewlett-Packard will be divided into two listed companies, separating the production of computers and printers from the faster-growing hardware and service sectors.
Deductions as a result of the expected reduction of jobs will be approximately 2.7 billion. US dollars since the fourth quarter, said in a statement Hewlett-Packard.
“Such a restructuring will provide a more competitive, sustainable cost structure for the new Hewlett Packard Enterprise,” said Meg Whitman, chairman and CEO of Hewlett Packard, who will lead the organization after the separation.
“Hewlett Packard Enterprise will be smaller and more focused than Hewlett-Packard at present, and the business portfolio will be wider and deeper, which will help the company move to a new business style,” Whitman said.
As a separate company, we are in a better position than before to respond to growing demands from our customers around the world.
Hewlett Packard Enterprise will have an annual revenue of more than $50 billion. US dollars and “will focus on providing previously unattainable integrated technology solutions” to companies, the company said in a statement.
So divides the company, formed in the 1930’s by Stanford University graduates Bill Hewlett and Dave Packard for the production of electrical equipment; their garage in Palo Alto was nicknamed “Silicon Valley’s birthplace.”
Hewlett Packard is in the process of a large-scale reorganization in order to move from traditional personal computers to mobile devices.
Such a move by HP, the world’s second-largest PC maker and one of the largest U.S. tech companies, is the latest event in this sector, based on the belief that highly specialized companies are working better.
