Glencore earns $2.5 billion on stock sales
The mining and commercial giant Glencore, which has hit the decline in commodity prices, earned $2.5 billion on the sale of shares as part of its grand plan to cut debt.
Glencore, quoted on the London Stock Exchange, has made a statement that he sold new shares worth about £1.6 billion to repay the debt.
The company, which has lost 57 percent of its market value, is trying to cope with the collapse in commodity prices while the downturn of China’s economy is degrading demand and creating chaos in global markets.
Thanks to the issuance of new shares at a discounted price, Glencore shares on the London Stock Exchange soared in early morning trading on Wednesday.
The shares jumped 2.77 percent to 131.60 pence on the FTSE 100 index, which at the opening was trading 0.69 percent higher.
Glencore last week began selling $2.5 billion in shares as part of extensive plans to cut its $30 billion in debt by about a third.
The company sold new shares for 125 cents apiece, that is, with a discount of 2.4 percent to the price when trading closes on Tuesday.
It placed 1.3 billion new shares, which is 9.99 percent of the authorized capital of the company.
Because of fears about the continuation of the recession in the Chinese economy, the cost of iron ore fell by about half, while coal, copper and other raw materials fell in price by 20-40 percent.
White House confirms Xi Jinping's visit to Washington
The White House on Tuesday confirmed in an official statement that Chinese President Xi Jinping will arrive on an official visit to the United States later this month.
This visit, Xi’s first visit to Washington, will take place on September 25 and will be a return visit to President Barack Obama’s arrival in Beijing last November.
U.S. President and First Lady Michelle Obama will also take Xi Jinping with his wife Peng Liyuan at a government dinner on the night of the same day after the two leaders hold bilateral talks.
“President’s visit Xi Jinping will provide an opportunity to expand cooperation between the United States and China on common, regional and bilateral issues of interest to both sides, and will allow the US and Chinese presidents to constructively approach the controversial topics,” the report said.
Xi Jinping, whose visit was first announced in February, is expected to stop in Seattle to meet with the leaders of several leading U.S. tech companies on their way to Washington, and then travel to New York to participate in the September UN General Assembly.
Obama and Xi Jingpin are expected to discuss a number of controversial issues, including Washington’s concerns related to alleged cyber espionage by China and China’s growing categoricality on the issue of the disputed South China Sea.
