Nobel laureate: globalization
Globalization processes should have contributed to reducing inequality in the world.
In fact, the situation looks different, the difference in the income of the population in developing economies, on the contrary, is growing.
Eric Maskin.
To correct this, it is necessary to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers, said the chief researcher of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Decision Selection of HSE, winner of the Nobel Prize in Economics in 2007. Eric Maskin.
In the past twenty years, the world has experienced unprecedented growth in global markets.
Trade borders between the countries were becoming more open.
Proponents of globalization predicted great benefits for developing economies.
“And these forecasts have largely come true,” Muskin emphasizes.
For example, China and India have received a serious GDP growth per capita.
But not everything is so rosy.
Globalization was expected to reduce the gap between “possessors” and “poor” in poor countries, which manifested in great inequality of income, or rather, wages.
But in fact, this inequality has only increased, notes Eric Muskin in his article “Why Global Markets Didn’t Reduce Inequality in Developing Economies,” published in The World Bank Economic Review, which was translated and quoted by HSE.
Together with Harvard University professor Michael Kremer, Eric Maskin, developed an alternative theory that demonstrates why income differences in poor countries increase as globalization grows, recalls HSE.
Specific processes are taking place in the new global market.
To demonstrate them, Maskin identifies four levels of expertise - A and B for rich countries, C and D - for the poor.
After globalization, D specialists from poor countries lack the level of qualification to cooperate with specialists A and B from rich countries.
And if workers in the level of C from poor countries are growing due to cooperation with employees B from the rich, then D workers do not feel growth or their salaries fall altogether.
The final effect is that internationalization of production will increase the pay gap between the two categories of professionals in poor countries and, accordingly, to increase the level of inequality.
Cremer and E. Maskins offer a surprisingly beautiful model, alternative to the Rycardian theory of comparative advantages.
It allows you to explain why globalization led to income inequality, says Fuad Aleskerov, an ordinary professor, head of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Decision Selection, Head of the HSE Department of Mathematics.
And as any powerful theory, I am sure, it will lead to a surge of empirical work in this field.
The solution to the problem, according to Eric Muskin, is to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers.
However, the workers themselves, as the scientist notes, do not have the means on this, and it is unprofitable for companies to pay for their training.
In such a situation, governments, international agencies, NGOs and private foundations can play a significant role, Maskin believes.
The scientist notes that the developed theory in no case calls for a halt in the process of globalization, which has brought and bears fruit in the form of GDP growth in countries.
