The Green Tribunal was quick to kill.
A typical situation: four officials are in front of the judge’s table of Judge Swanter Kumar, listening to his claims to the work done.
The court is completely dissatisfied with the quality of your work.
We didn’t give you a 110-page order to make you laugh at him, says Kumar. -
If there is at least one more brick, we will order to demolish all the existing buildings.
Kumar heads the National Green Tribunal (NWT), a judicial authority established in 2010 to stop the rapid pollution of the environment, accompanied by the rapid economic growth of recent decades.
During this time, the Tribunal managed to consider more than 10 thousand claims related to air pollution, garbage collection, geological developments, toxic waste and the construction of dams.
In two out of three cases, the court decides to stop the construction leading to pollution.
The stakes are incredibly high: in the incomplete 60 years since the independence of the strengthened industrial development, India has turned from a country of virgin jungle into one of the most overpopulated and polluted countries in the world.
The problem is especially acute in large megacities, where the development of infrastructure does not improve for rapid urbanization: cities are covered with dense smog, the rivers are filled with pesticides and waste of enterprises and households, and the remaining residential areas are cut down for construction with new residential areas.
Despite the formal support of the green movement by the state, NRT is regularly criticized by the government of Narendra Modi, as it often becomes the main reason for the cancellation of the largest investment projects.
So, in May of this year, the Minister of Environment called the court’s decisions “extreme” and “impossible”.
Sometimes court decisions are really impossible to fulfill within the period set by the court, confirms the lawyer for environmental cases Raj Panjwani.
However, the impossible deadlines have a positive side: at least, they force responsible persons to move.
“His main goal is to shake this system,” the lawyer adds.
The Green Tribunal has repeatedly canceled major construction projects: the termination of the airport, power plant and hundreds of smaller facilities.
At the same time, people are also trying not to forget: for example, during the discussion of the fate of a pharmaceutical company in the state of Telagnan, which polluted the local river with fluoride.
We can close your factory, but we are responsible for the economic consequences.
“People will lose their jobs,” Kumar commented on his decision.
However, such explanations do not always find understanding among ordinary people whose lives can change thanks to one stroke of the judicial pen.
In April, the Tribunal decided to ban all vehicles over 10 years of age from entering the capital, which caused public outrage.
Despite the sharply fallen popularity and a flurry of criticism, Swantter Kumar refused to cancel this decision.
Instead, he ordered statistics from the government of Delhi about entering and outgoing vehicles, and also made an offer to purchase 10 thousand additional buses, having previously learned in the factories whether they are able to fulfill such an order.
As the attention of the court began to get sources of pollution such as landfills, fuel quality and even road accidents, popular anger began to subside.
But the most painful topic of the principal judge was the program to clean the Ganges River, with pompom announced by Prime Minister Narendra Modi last year.
When it comes to the Ganges, a sacred river for Hindus, the judge often stops restraining his emotions and turning into a cry.
Do you know what the word "holy" means?
Someone poured water from the Ganges on the statue of God, and there were feces in it, the judge is hot. -
You continue to pollute the river because you think it's Ganges, he'll take all our sins.
It’s the river we worship and see what you do with it every day.
Cleaning the Ganges is the most ambitious and expensive environmental project announced by the new government.
Currently, the number of fecal bacteria in this river exceeds the norm by more than 120 times.
Every year, 1.5 to 3 out of 700 million women bathing in it die from infectious diseases.
In February, Narendra Modi even donated money to the Ganges Rescue Fund, the proceeds from the sale of his suit, in which he dated Barack Obama and another 455 items from his personal collection.
Environmentalists immediately accused the prime minister of populism: the suit was bought for 700 thousand dollars, while at least eight billion is required for cleaning the river.
Supporters of the Green Tribunal agree that India is still a long way to go before it can call itself a developed country, but does not believe that the price of progress should be ecology.
“In a developing country, talk about the environment is often perceived as an impermissible luxury,” says Malika Bhanot, an activist at Zov Ganges. -
And the court is trying to find a middle ground between ecology and development.”
