Xi Jinping calls for economics to be more open to the world
The economy should become more open to the world to spur its growth, as President Xi Jinping said on Tuesday in an address to a group that is tasked with leadership reforms.
“China should focus on attracting foreign investors and experts and developing a policy of openness,” he said, addressing the participants of the 16-th meeting of the Committee of the Central Lead Group for the Comprehensive Deepening of Reforms.
According to him, the expansion of openness and deepening of reforms will give the economy a new impetus and vitality and will provide a new space for economic development.
The leading group adopted a number of directives, including the introduction of market access regulation, change the rules of border control, the promotion of state-owned enterprises (SOE), attracting private capital and the revision of the registration system for residents.
According to the statement, a list of sectors of the economy and production will be compiled, inaccessible to investment.
The system will be gradually adjusted through trial programs.
This is an important step, as it will provide the market with a more significant role in the distribution of resources, ensuring legality in the business sphere and increasing openness, as stated in the statement.
The government will also weaken control over the powers granted to them to companies, thereby ensuring that companies themselves will conduct their own business.
The statement also said that China will allow the border regions to develop new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to strengthen local growth.
Even more areas will be available to private investors in order to increase the openness of state-controlled sectors of the economy.
“The government will not change its policy towards foreign investors and will protect the legitimate interests of companies with foreign financing, as well as provide them with better conditions,” the statement said.
In addition, the procedure for applying for a permanent residence permit for foreigners, or “grung-person card”, will be facilitated by optimizing requirements and simplifying the filing process itself.
The meeting also discussed the rights of lawyers and the training of professional judges and prosecutors.
According to the official report issued after the meeting, it was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang and Ministers Liu Yongshan and Zhang Gaoli.
